This article discusses an executive order issued by President Barack Obama on January 22, 2009, regarding the closure of detention facilities at Guantanamo Bay Naval Base and the review and disposition of individuals detained there. The order states that the facilities must be closed as soon as possible, and no later than one year from the date of the order. The review of detainees will be conducted by various officials, including the Attorney General, Secretary of Defense, Secretary of State, and others. The review will determine whether detainees can be transferred or released, if they should be prosecuted, or if other means of disposition are necessary. The order also emphasizes the importance of conducting the review in accordance with applicable laws and ensuring humane standards of confinement. The Secretary of State is instructed to pursue diplomatic efforts with foreign governments to implement the order. The order also calls for a halt to military commission proceedings during the review. The order concludes with general provisions and emphasizes that it does not create any enforceable rights or benefits against the United States or its entities.